40
00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:43.940
Okay. Well, thanks for the kind introduction.

41
00:02:44.060 --> 00:02:47.140
Thanks to everybody for being here so early on the last day.

42
00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:51.260
It's a real honor for me to be here today, and I'll talk about

43
00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:55.460
theranostics, and perhaps some of you can consider

44
00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:57.640
bringing these into your practices.

45
00:02:58.700 --> 00:02:59.920
So, some disclosures.

46
00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:04.420
So by way of outline, first I'll talk about precision imaging.

47
00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:08.320
I'll talk about imaging and therapy, which is sort of the backbone of

48
00:03:08.340 --> 00:03:09.070
theranostics,

49
00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:12.609
emerging targets, and then I'll give a perspective at the end.

50
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.960
So when we think about precision medicine, we think of it as a

51
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.360
genetic phenomenon where a patient's genome or their

52
00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:25.040
epigenome might determine what sort of precise,

53
00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:27.410
exact therapy that they might be getting.

54
00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:31.280
But to me, I look at the genetics somewhat as on-the-ground

55
00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:35.260
intelligence about the patient, whereas with imaging, we

56
00:03:35.340 --> 00:03:38.920
have spatial information. So now we can design

57
00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:42.400
guided missiles to be able to take out various malignant

58
00:03:42.540 --> 00:03:46.260
lesions very specifically, going after specific targets.

59
00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:50.980
So one thing that we could do, with precision imaging, is that we can subtype

60
00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:54.680
disease. So patients A and B have very

61
00:03:54.690 --> 00:03:58.500
similar phenotypes. They both have high-risk prostate cancer.

62
00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:01.860
I think it was Gleason 9 prostate cancer.

63
00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:05.880
But with this precision imaging agent, we see that

64
00:04:05.900 --> 00:04:08.920
patient A has localized disease. Patient

65
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.480
B already has disseminated disease.

66
00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:15.540
So these two patients are going to have vastly different journeys with their

67
00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:18.000
cancer. So we can subtype the disease.

68
00:04:18.041 --> 00:04:21.399
They may even have different types of prostate cancer.

69
00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:25.020
So that's what we can now do with precision

70
00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:25.560
imaging.

71
00:04:26.700 --> 00:04:30.140
So when we think about what imaging is for, we think about how it

72
00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:33.780
decreases mortality by screening, decreases cost,

73
00:04:33.860 --> 00:04:37.650
decreases length of an episode of care, but these are really

74
00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:40.380
somewhat conventional ways to think about imaging.

75
00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:44.440
But now, with precision imaging, we now have

76
00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:48.200
proteogenomics, so we can find new targets for

77
00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:52.090
imaging, for molecular imaging. There are new ways of generating

78
00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:54.360
affinity probes to those targets.

79
00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:58.500
Chemistry is a little bit simpler than it

80
00:04:58.540 --> 00:05:00.740
was when I was in graduate school. Now they have

81
00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:05.960
click chemistry. We don't have to be organic chemists to make

82
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.840
these things always. We have very highly relevant

83
00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:13.320
genetic animal models of a human disease.

84
00:05:13.780 --> 00:05:16.620
Very sensitive new devices like total body PET.

85
00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:20.720
Everything we do is on our computers.

86
00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:25.200
But probably the most important advance in not just

87
00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:29.170
imaging, not just medicine, and seemingly in life these days,

88
00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:33.160
is that all this work, and most of the work that we do now,

89
00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:37.720
is able to be collated, annotated, analyzed, and utilized through

90
00:05:37.780 --> 00:05:38.790
cloud computing,

91
00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:42.360
and I'll mention a couple things about that toward the end.

92
00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:47.680
So my former collaborator at Johns Hopkins, Bert Vogelstein,

93
00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:51.640
had this paper out about now 10 years ago, where he said that

94
00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:55.660
variation in cancer risk among tissues can be explained by the number of stem cell

95
00:05:55.740 --> 00:05:56.280
divisions.

96
00:05:57.120 --> 00:06:00.590
So a little bit complicated title, but if you pull out

97
00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:04.600
the abstract, it says that, "Only a third of the variation in cancer risk

98
00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:07.640
among tissues is attributable to environmental factors or inherited

99
00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:10.620
predispositions. The majority is due to bad

100
00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:14.620
luck."So we don't hear bad luck often in science papers.

101
00:06:15.340 --> 00:06:19.220
But what I think that Bert means by this is that no matter

102
00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:23.040
how much kale you eat, and no matter how much time you spend on the

103
00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:26.670
elliptical, two-thirds of the time, cancer is

104
00:06:27.020 --> 00:06:27.639
bad luck.

105
00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:32.140
So his solution is to detect it as early as

106
00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:35.180
possible, and he does that using circulating tumor DNA.

107
00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:40.110
And to do it with circulating tumor DNA, you need about 50 million cells,

108
00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:42.720
which is a number I'd like you to remember for a minute.

109
00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:46.840
That's one way to detect cancer. We're going to do it

110
00:06:47.460 --> 00:06:48.320
through imaging.

111
00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:53.280
Now, when I was a junior faculty member, I was a

112
00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:56.260
neuroradiologist. I was interested in

113
00:06:56.400 --> 00:06:58.640
glutamatergic neurotransmission.

114
00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:03.640
And in order to image glutamate in the brain, I

115
00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:06.420
thought that if there were an enzyme

116
00:07:07.340 --> 00:07:11.160
such as nalidase, that we could somehow

117
00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:15.220
label with a positron-emitting affinity agent, that

118
00:07:15.240 --> 00:07:18.840
we'd be able to map out where glutamate is happening in the brain,

119
00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:23.520
and it would be something that would be important because glutamate's a

120
00:07:23.560 --> 00:07:27.460
very important transmitter. And this particular paper that I just came

121
00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:31.460
across just by chance, I saw they had very high affinity

122
00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:35.230
inhibitors, but the inhibitors were very hydrophilic,

123
00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:39.200
and they looked a lot like the natural substrate for the enzyme,

124
00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:43.410
NaAG, and they weren't going to get across the blood-brain barrier.

125
00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:47.820
So I put this project on a back burner as soon as I

126
00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:51.280
saw this paper at the same time back in 1996.

127
00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:55.070
This is a paper by Joe Coyle's group where he showed that

128
00:07:55.070 --> 00:07:58.830
prostate-specific membrane antigen was the same as

129
00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:02.760
that brain enzyme. So I immediately pivoted everything to

130
00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:06.660
prostate cancer and said, "Forget about schizophrenia

131
00:08:06.670 --> 00:08:09.620
and Alzheimer's disease, et cetera, and let's work on this.

132
00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:13.720
No blood-brain barrier here." So we can develop small molecule

133
00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:17.640
agents for prostate cancer. So at the time,

134
00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:19.820
in the mid-'90s, there was an agent.

135
00:08:19.860 --> 00:08:23.240
It was an antibody agent, for detecting

136
00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:27.180
PSMA for prostate cancer. But it didn't work particularly

137
00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:31.240
well. The images were not particularly visually appealing.

138
00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:35.000
So we thought that a small molecule might have better

139
00:08:35.020 --> 00:08:38.909
pharmacokinetics, and we can get clearer, crisper pictures of prostate cancer.

140
00:08:39.701 --> 00:08:43.640
So after many years, we eventually developed this

141
00:08:43.701 --> 00:08:47.120
compound labeled with fluorine-18, which is for positron emission

142
00:08:47.140 --> 00:08:47.700
tomography,

143
00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:52.600
and we're able to image very tiny lesions like this lesion in

144
00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:53.120
the marrow.

145
00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:57.780
Now, the idea here is to change the way that we manage

146
00:08:58.060 --> 00:09:01.260
prostate cancer, potentially, if we're going to integrate imaging.

147
00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:05.160
So Dr. Vogelstein needs about 50 million cells.

148
00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:09.420
We need on the same order of cells. So if somebody

149
00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:13.240
is at high risk for metastasis, you might

150
00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:17.540
have the blood test first. If there's a hit, then we could come in and

151
00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:20.120
use the somewhat more expensive imaging study.

152
00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:22.500
We can see exactly where the lesion is.

153
00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:26.520
We could call our friends like Phu Tran, who's a radiation oncologist.

154
00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:30.320
He could do stereotactic radiation, and he could take out that lesion before the

155
00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:32.520
patient even feels that they're ill.

156
00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:37.020
So the point is to get the disease while it's just oligo

157
00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:38.700
rather than polymetastatic.

158
00:09:40.060 --> 00:09:44.020
So we kept working on these agents to image

159
00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:47.820
prostate cancer targeting PSMA, and we learned

160
00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:51.500
that we needed about a 20 Angstrom linker

161
00:09:51.540 --> 00:09:54.960
between the affinity part, this urea, and the

162
00:09:55.040 --> 00:09:58.020
chelator in order to get productive binding to PSMA.

163
00:09:58.860 --> 00:10:02.840
So this way, we could start putting radiometals attached to our

164
00:10:02.849 --> 00:10:06.420
affinity agents. So now, we can image, and then we can

165
00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:09.840
potentially use molecular radiotherapeutics.

166
00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:13.330
That's kind of what theranostics are, and this is what got us into

167
00:10:13.330 --> 00:10:16.480
theranostics. We also showed that the small

168
00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:20.000
molecules would be able to be internalized, just like the

169
00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:24.020
antibodies could be. Internalization is a good quality for

170
00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:27.189
a theranostic because then you get long residence times and long

171
00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:30.659
exposures of the

172
00:10:30.860 --> 00:10:34.480
particulate emissions to the tumor, which I'll talk about in a minute.

173
00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:37.350
So theranostics can

174
00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:41.740
be used at many different points during the patient's

175
00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:45.680
journey. But we're going to focus over here on sort of

176
00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:49.340
this image-based guidance, specifically radiodiagnosis,

177
00:10:49.480 --> 00:10:50.440
radiotherapy.

178
00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:54.560
So the theranostic agent really has three parts to it.

179
00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:58.580
It's got the affinity agent, the substrate, what binds to your target.

180
00:10:58.620 --> 00:11:02.430
It's got a linker, which is often a chelating agent for a radiometal,

181
00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:06.720
which can either be a imaging or diagnostic or a therapeutic

182
00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:10.600
nuclide. So for imaging or for therapy, that's what theranostics

183
00:11:10.620 --> 00:11:13.580
is. I put the word target in red here because

184
00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:16.640
the target is the most important thing.

185
00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:18.620
Okay, so once you have the target,

186
00:11:19.580 --> 00:11:23.300
chances are you're going to be able to figure out how to engage that target

187
00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:27.300
productively. It may not take overnight, but

188
00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:30.420
you'll be able to figure it out, particularly with new technologies, as I'll

189
00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:34.380
discuss. You want that target, if it's biologically

190
00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:38.360
important, all the better. You want its expression restricted to the

191
00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:42.260
tumor. You want it in high concentrations in the tumor, high affinity

192
00:11:42.400 --> 00:11:46.320
for your agent, suitable pharmacokinetics for the drug that

193
00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:48.160
you're giving. These are essentially drugs.

194
00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:52.160
You want long residence time and internalization to match the

195
00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:55.640
pharmacokinetics between your physical

196
00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:59.440
half-life on your radionuclide and your agent that you're

197
00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:02.200
giving, and then, of course, you want limited off-target effects.

198
00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:06.420
The bottom line is that these compounds are all synthesized and

199
00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:10.280
optimized using the tools of medicinal chemistry just like anything

200
00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:13.570
else with a few differences,

201
00:12:14.120 --> 00:12:18.070
and that's why we're beginning to see a lot more medicinal chemists and

202
00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:22.086
other chemists that are getting into the business.So these are

203
00:12:22.116 --> 00:12:25.586
the radiotheranostics that are currently in clinical development.

204
00:12:25.916 --> 00:12:29.816
This is just some of the theranostics for

205
00:12:29.836 --> 00:12:32.416
prostate cancer, specifically for PSMA.

206
00:12:33.536 --> 00:12:35.176
Now, there are many other targets

207
00:12:36.036 --> 00:12:39.136
that can be used for prostate cancer, whether you want a

208
00:12:39.196 --> 00:12:42.976
castration-resistant disease or potentially neuroendocrine

209
00:12:43.016 --> 00:12:46.736
prostate cancer. So little by little, the more we learn about these

210
00:12:46.796 --> 00:12:49.056
targets, the more we can do about the cancer.

211
00:12:49.576 --> 00:12:53.355
So we, in imaging or in chemistry, rely very

212
00:12:53.395 --> 00:12:57.076
heavily on you to find targets that

213
00:12:57.356 --> 00:12:58.636
we can act upon.

214
00:12:59.476 --> 00:13:02.396
So this just shows that there are other targets.

215
00:13:02.456 --> 00:13:04.516
The two main targets right now that are being

216
00:13:05.356 --> 00:13:09.136
approached are SSTR2 and PSMA, but

217
00:13:09.216 --> 00:13:12.576
many others are coming along, carbonic anhydrase,

218
00:13:12.656 --> 00:13:15.056
CD45, and others.

219
00:13:16.296 --> 00:13:20.216
In terms of the preclinical world, there are hundreds, I

220
00:13:20.276 --> 00:13:20.756
don't know, maybe

221
00:13:21.556 --> 00:13:25.496
1,000 new targets that are being pursued, shown here in this very

222
00:13:25.536 --> 00:13:29.426
nice recent article. And the nuclides are shown

223
00:13:29.796 --> 00:13:33.696
and the affinity agents. So all these different things have to be optimized to

224
00:13:33.736 --> 00:13:35.076
get this to work.

225
00:13:36.276 --> 00:13:40.036
So just in the last few years, this slide, I couldn't have

226
00:13:40.076 --> 00:13:43.816
shown this slide five years ago, but in the last few years,

227
00:13:44.976 --> 00:13:47.916
industry, commercial entities have gotten very interested.

228
00:13:47.976 --> 00:13:51.896
This is in the US and Canada, despite the fact that there are really only a

229
00:13:52.016 --> 00:13:55.956
very few of these theranostics that have been approved, that have gone

230
00:13:55.976 --> 00:13:57.296
through registration trials.

231
00:13:58.356 --> 00:14:01.526
This is in Europe. In the Middle East, there's another set of companies.

232
00:14:01.916 --> 00:14:05.876
In Australia and Asia. And this has really sparked interest

233
00:14:05.916 --> 00:14:09.836
in the field, which is why even though I've been working in this area for 40

234
00:14:09.896 --> 00:14:13.756
years and no one seemed to care about it, as soon as Novartis

235
00:14:13.816 --> 00:14:17.576
got involved and it shows that these things work to a

236
00:14:17.616 --> 00:14:21.096
certain extent, that's when everybody began to pay attention.

237
00:14:21.816 --> 00:14:25.656
So really what we're talking about are beta emissions and alpha emissions.

238
00:14:25.696 --> 00:14:29.506
Beta particles or electrons need a couple hundred decays,

239
00:14:30.016 --> 00:14:31.176
single strand breaks.

240
00:14:32.036 --> 00:14:34.116
Those are not as strong as alpha emitters.

241
00:14:34.176 --> 00:14:37.916
Helium nuclei, these cause double strand breaks, very hard for the

242
00:14:37.976 --> 00:14:41.936
cells to repair. So I think the future is sort of moving

243
00:14:41.976 --> 00:14:44.576
a little bit more toward alpha particle emitters.

244
00:14:45.496 --> 00:14:49.456
But the beta emitters are what are in widespread use now, and this slide's

245
00:14:49.516 --> 00:14:51.876
already about maybe seven or eight years old,

246
00:14:52.736 --> 00:14:55.876
but what this shows is the PSMA 617.

247
00:14:55.916 --> 00:14:58.996
It's essentially a radiochemical debulking of tumor.

248
00:14:59.756 --> 00:15:03.736
So you can take patients with PSAs close to 1,000 and reduce

249
00:15:03.756 --> 00:15:07.016
them almost to nothing and wipe out just about all the tumor

250
00:15:07.216 --> 00:15:10.256
visually, at least the PSMA positive tumor.

251
00:15:10.656 --> 00:15:14.496
Tremendously good for quality of life as

252
00:15:14.636 --> 00:15:14.956
well.

253
00:15:16.776 --> 00:15:20.585
So one reason that you might think about bringing these into your practice is that

254
00:15:20.585 --> 00:15:24.456
they're safe and effective. So you could see that the PSA

255
00:15:24.716 --> 00:15:27.276
50 declines are

256
00:15:28.156 --> 00:15:32.016
better than they are for cabazitaxel, and they tend to be much

257
00:15:32.036 --> 00:15:34.736
milder in terms of the side effects.

258
00:15:35.296 --> 00:15:39.136
So even though I'm a radiologist, I have patients that call and say, "How can I get

259
00:15:39.196 --> 00:15:42.696
some of this? I don't want to take chemo." So it's

260
00:15:43.096 --> 00:15:45.736
a very nice new agent in that regard.

261
00:15:47.496 --> 00:15:51.456
So alpha emitters. So pivoting here, there are

262
00:15:51.496 --> 00:15:53.896
kind of the two biggies are actinium and lead.

263
00:15:54.476 --> 00:15:56.676
I'm going to advocate a little bit for astatine.

264
00:15:57.436 --> 00:16:00.596
And astatine, also an alpha emitter, shorter physical half-life.

265
00:16:01.376 --> 00:16:05.296
What I like about it is there's only one alpha decay, so you have

266
00:16:05.356 --> 00:16:07.456
full control over where your

267
00:16:09.016 --> 00:16:12.496
decay is going to be deposited. It's going to be deposited in the tumor.

268
00:16:13.376 --> 00:16:17.175
For actinium, for example, there's a recoil

269
00:16:17.296 --> 00:16:19.536
after the first decay, and you may

270
00:16:20.396 --> 00:16:23.396
somehow lose track of where those other alpha decays are going to happen.

271
00:16:23.416 --> 00:16:26.086
They may not happen in the tumor. Anyway, this is all

272
00:16:26.656 --> 00:16:29.456
theoretical. But astatine is also nice.

273
00:16:29.516 --> 00:16:33.396
It's a halogen. It can be incorporated into small molecules

274
00:16:33.436 --> 00:16:35.936
without disrupting the pharmacokinetics too much.

275
00:16:36.425 --> 00:16:39.096
So we could start thinking about intracellular targets.

276
00:16:39.175 --> 00:16:41.495
We don't just have to be on the cell surface all the time.

277
00:16:42.256 --> 00:16:45.936
So astatine is something that we've been focusing on, and I've been

278
00:16:45.996 --> 00:16:49.876
working with Michael Ziolkowski, and after a

279
00:16:49.916 --> 00:16:53.396
fair amount of optimization, we developed a compound that

280
00:16:53.736 --> 00:16:56.576
binds PSMA labeled with astatine.

281
00:16:56.836 --> 00:17:00.276
We interestingly have a chelator out here mainly for pharmacokinetic

282
00:17:00.336 --> 00:17:03.996
purposes, not for actual radioactivity or

283
00:17:04.076 --> 00:17:06.017
distributing the radioactivity.

284
00:17:06.876 --> 00:17:10.757
There are a lot of nuances that I think are not

285
00:17:11.576 --> 00:17:15.436
bad to mention when you're developing these kind of compounds.

286
00:17:15.656 --> 00:17:18.896
For example, the idea of carrier or non-radiolabeled

287
00:17:18.936 --> 00:17:22.556
material that binds the same receptor as

288
00:17:23.116 --> 00:17:27.036
the radiolabeled material. You can modify

289
00:17:27.116 --> 00:17:30.476
how much off-target effect that you get if you add

290
00:17:30.536 --> 00:17:33.816
carrier or if you make material that has lower specific

291
00:17:33.896 --> 00:17:37.776
radioactivity. You might get a little bit less uptake in the tumor, but you

292
00:17:37.816 --> 00:17:41.016
get much, much less in the off-target sites.

293
00:17:41.476 --> 00:17:44.176
So that's one way to keep these things safer.

294
00:17:45.636 --> 00:17:49.456
Another thing about astatine is that you can actually image it directly.

295
00:17:50.216 --> 00:17:53.776
So this is a SPECT scan, and we can see that directly.

296
00:17:53.876 --> 00:17:57.756
We can use this for doing precision dosimetry if we really

297
00:17:57.796 --> 00:17:59.196
want to. Right now,

298
00:18:00.156 --> 00:18:01.876
everyone gets kind of the same dose.

299
00:18:02.316 --> 00:18:04.696
It's easy to do, easy to work into the clinic.

300
00:18:05.316 --> 00:18:08.656
But we may go toward precision dosimetry in the future.

301
00:18:09.996 --> 00:18:13.736
So there's a lot of other targets. There's a whole list, and you could read

302
00:18:13.796 --> 00:18:17.536
about the other targets. We had focused on

303
00:18:17.656 --> 00:18:19.916
carbonic anhydrase IX using small

304
00:18:19.996 --> 00:18:23.916
moleculeinhibitors. And you can see

305
00:18:23.956 --> 00:18:27.836
the primary tumor here. You could see that there are lesions in

306
00:18:27.876 --> 00:18:31.686
the upper mediastinum. We do have some

307
00:18:31.716 --> 00:18:35.636
gastric uptake. I think that's an undesirable on-target

308
00:18:35.676 --> 00:18:38.606
effect, so we still need to work on that a little bit

309
00:18:38.636 --> 00:18:42.036
further. Another very common target is fibroblast

310
00:18:42.116 --> 00:18:43.636
activation protein.

311
00:18:44.616 --> 00:18:46.416
This is in the tumor microenvironment.

312
00:18:46.456 --> 00:18:50.356
The advantage here is that FAP is present in almost all solid tumors,

313
00:18:50.836 --> 00:18:52.636
so I think it's going to be great for imaging.

314
00:18:53.216 --> 00:18:57.096
The first compound that we made a long time ago had very

315
00:18:57.136 --> 00:18:59.066
high affinity, picomolar affinity.

316
00:18:59.876 --> 00:19:02.216
However, we couldn't image anything with it.

317
00:19:02.836 --> 00:19:06.626
It wouldn't image the tumors, and I believe it's because there was

318
00:19:06.716 --> 00:19:10.556
a secreted version of FAP that was mopping

319
00:19:10.616 --> 00:19:13.996
up our imaging agent. And we learned that when we

320
00:19:14.036 --> 00:19:17.896
gave higher amounts of carrier, we show that we were

321
00:19:17.976 --> 00:19:21.856
able to block the nonspecific binding in blood

322
00:19:21.876 --> 00:19:25.506
and get more uptake in the tumor. So I'm showing this

323
00:19:25.536 --> 00:19:29.256
mainly because there are lots of different things that you have to juggle in order

324
00:19:29.296 --> 00:19:32.936
to keep them safe and in order to get adequate signal to

325
00:19:32.996 --> 00:19:33.476
noise.

326
00:19:34.476 --> 00:19:37.166
So just a couple of weeks ago, we took our

327
00:19:37.856 --> 00:19:41.676
compound, different than this, and we

328
00:19:41.736 --> 00:19:45.336
finally showed a very nice primary... Well, very nice.

329
00:19:45.396 --> 00:19:48.756
A terrible primary tumor in this patient with pancreatic cancer

330
00:19:49.476 --> 00:19:53.336
and several lesions in the liver. We changed the management, and this is our

331
00:19:53.376 --> 00:19:56.916
very first research subject, because you couldn't see these

332
00:19:57.136 --> 00:20:01.096
liver lesions on CT or on MR. So

333
00:20:01.156 --> 00:20:03.456
that's what we can do now with precision imaging.

334
00:20:03.496 --> 00:20:04.816
We hope to turn that into a

335
00:20:06.256 --> 00:20:06.866
therapeutic.

336
00:20:07.736 --> 00:20:11.616
So, a little perspective. Doors have been opened

337
00:20:11.656 --> 00:20:15.456
with advances in many different areas, all at the

338
00:20:15.536 --> 00:20:19.416
same time over the last five or six years to enable us to

339
00:20:19.456 --> 00:20:22.916
get to where we are, but there's really a tremendous amount for us to do.

340
00:20:23.856 --> 00:20:27.316
So this is the VISION trial, the registration trial for the PSMA

341
00:20:27.556 --> 00:20:31.456
617, and even though this is life-prolonging

342
00:20:31.556 --> 00:20:34.716
therapy if you add it to standard care, you don't

343
00:20:34.736 --> 00:20:38.076
really prolong life that much. This is overall survival.

344
00:20:38.156 --> 00:20:41.806
I think progression-free survival increase was about five months.

345
00:20:42.796 --> 00:20:46.676
So the Kaplan-Meier curves to me, despite the fact that these

346
00:20:46.716 --> 00:20:50.556
patients were terribly ill, still too close

347
00:20:50.596 --> 00:20:51.006
together,

348
00:20:51.956 --> 00:20:55.456
and especially if you take a look at what this does to the cancer

349
00:20:55.496 --> 00:20:59.336
itself. So what this tells me is that we're leaving

350
00:20:59.376 --> 00:21:03.306
maybe one or two clones behind, and then it comes back, and

351
00:21:03.336 --> 00:21:05.816
unfortunately, the Kaplan-Meier curves are close together.

352
00:21:06.896 --> 00:21:07.376
So now,

353
00:21:08.356 --> 00:21:12.256
many groups around the world are trying to pry those Kaplan-Meier curves

354
00:21:12.296 --> 00:21:16.176
apart. So for example, I like this very

355
00:21:16.556 --> 00:21:17.296
interesting study

356
00:21:18.296 --> 00:21:21.976
called LUNAR, where they do a neoadjuvant debulking

357
00:21:22.056 --> 00:21:26.006
with the molecular radiotherapy, and then they do metastasis-directed

358
00:21:26.056 --> 00:21:30.026
stereotactic radiation. And now they find that they get

359
00:21:30.316 --> 00:21:33.496
a little bit more progression-free survival that way.

360
00:21:33.656 --> 00:21:36.856
So incrementally, I think that we're going to leverage these

361
00:21:36.896 --> 00:21:40.796
theranostics along with other entities so that we can really

362
00:21:41.076 --> 00:21:44.776
be able to manage these patients. So what are the challenges in the

363
00:21:44.816 --> 00:21:47.156
field? Right now, we need more people to do it.

364
00:21:47.456 --> 00:21:51.096
It's generally led by nuclear medicine physicians.

365
00:21:51.156 --> 00:21:54.796
We need more personnel. That's just the delivery of the

366
00:21:54.856 --> 00:21:58.836
agents. We need more people to synthesize the compounds, to dig

367
00:21:58.916 --> 00:22:02.606
up the radioisotopes. There's a huge

368
00:22:02.696 --> 00:22:03.476
supply chain.

369
00:22:04.356 --> 00:22:06.436
We're not quite sure how to dose patients now.

370
00:22:06.516 --> 00:22:07.536
Right now, as I mentioned,

371
00:22:08.456 --> 00:22:10.476
everybody gets kind of the same dose.

372
00:22:11.156 --> 00:22:14.556
We need to make that more precise. The tumors are notorious

373
00:22:14.636 --> 00:22:18.306
heterogeneous. There's lineage plasticity, so these things will

374
00:22:18.356 --> 00:22:21.156
adapt to androgen receptor

375
00:22:22.636 --> 00:22:26.316
inhibitors. There's mutations that occur, so they're very

376
00:22:26.356 --> 00:22:30.176
heterogeneous, both between patients, within the patient, within the tumor.

377
00:22:30.756 --> 00:22:32.396
All these things have to be overcome.

378
00:22:33.596 --> 00:22:36.896
Supply chain is a little bit of a challenge. Who gets these things?

379
00:22:36.956 --> 00:22:40.846
They're very expensive. Do you have to be a millionaire to get them, or

380
00:22:40.956 --> 00:22:44.256
can anyone get them who could benefit from them?

381
00:22:44.646 --> 00:22:47.586
And then the uncertainty of federal funding is important because

382
00:22:48.496 --> 00:22:52.096
just about all the discoveries in all of these

383
00:22:52.136 --> 00:22:55.376
different targets, and frankly, all the supporting

384
00:22:55.456 --> 00:22:58.756
biology tends to happen in academic labs.

385
00:22:59.376 --> 00:23:02.796
So all that work that we did with PSMA was funded by the

386
00:23:03.096 --> 00:23:05.436
NIH, and now that's a little bit uncertain.

387
00:23:06.096 --> 00:23:09.776
So I'll end by just talking about a few things that I think are going to be

388
00:23:09.816 --> 00:23:10.976
important going forward.

389
00:23:11.876 --> 00:23:15.456
AI, of course. So AI now can be

390
00:23:15.576 --> 00:23:16.316
used for

391
00:23:17.876 --> 00:23:21.536
discovering new targets, the whole pipeline for lead

392
00:23:21.716 --> 00:23:24.216
discovery, optimization, et cetera.

393
00:23:26.096 --> 00:23:29.996
My colleague Yong Du has built a human scanner

394
00:23:30.196 --> 00:23:33.916
specifically for interrogating the distribution of alpha particle

395
00:23:33.976 --> 00:23:37.896
emitters in the body so we can do precision dosimetry.

396
00:23:37.976 --> 00:23:39.926
We could see what the pharmacokinetics look like.

397
00:23:40.576 --> 00:23:43.366
He uses AI-based algorithms to do his imaging.

398
00:23:44.316 --> 00:23:45.726
Imaging is not just

399
00:23:46.576 --> 00:23:48.596
nice pictures, imaging is data.

400
00:23:49.536 --> 00:23:53.476
But I do want to say one thing, one caution about the magic

401
00:23:53.536 --> 00:23:57.336
of artificial intelligence is that you can teach a

402
00:23:57.356 --> 00:24:00.786
convolutional neural network on a million bone scans,

403
00:24:01.356 --> 00:24:04.436
and it'll be able to interpret that bone scan.

404
00:24:04.996 --> 00:24:08.836
But in this real-life situation, where one of the radiation oncologists asked us,

405
00:24:08.896 --> 00:24:10.936
"Should we go ahead and irradiate this thing here?

406
00:24:11.016 --> 00:24:13.196
You said it was a possible metastasis."

407
00:24:14.276 --> 00:24:15.356
So we suggested,

408
00:24:16.236 --> 00:24:19.856
before it was approved by the FDA, that you use one of our imaging

409
00:24:19.956 --> 00:24:23.456
agents, and we showed that by using the imaging agent that there was actually more

410
00:24:23.516 --> 00:24:27.040
cancer in that patient than met the eye.So you could

411
00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:31.020
see that we're still a little bit ahead of the machines, at

412
00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:34.670
least just for a few years. And now we're training the machines on

413
00:24:34.720 --> 00:24:38.660
these images so that we can get even closer

414
00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:39.520
to where we need to be.

415
00:24:40.640 --> 00:24:44.620
So for example, now we can automatically, this is a fully automated pipeline

416
00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:47.620
where we could automatically detect and localize the lesions.

417
00:24:48.060 --> 00:24:51.880
We can segment the lesions, extract features from them, combine

418
00:24:51.900 --> 00:24:55.060
that information with the protected health information.

419
00:24:55.640 --> 00:24:58.800
We can hopefully start providing very specific

420
00:24:58.880 --> 00:25:02.520
recommendations to patients. But overall, the idea of bringing

421
00:25:02.620 --> 00:25:06.560
AI into this workflow is that we want to be able to combine the power

422
00:25:06.660 --> 00:25:10.240
of AI and the sensitivity and specificity of

423
00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:13.360
molecular imaging so that we can get as close to human

424
00:25:13.420 --> 00:25:16.840
biochemistry non-invasively as possible.

425
00:25:18.920 --> 00:25:22.880
Number two is we have a rational comb-- I think there's a lot of

426
00:25:22.920 --> 00:25:25.360
possibilities for rational combinations.

427
00:25:25.940 --> 00:25:29.000
I personally tend to like those that have an immunological

428
00:25:29.040 --> 00:25:32.270
component. This was a new trial that came out, PRINCE,

429
00:25:33.260 --> 00:25:36.660
and this is where they do tumor debulking, then they give the checkpoint inhibitor.

430
00:25:37.180 --> 00:25:41.020
The PSA 50 was 76%, the PSA 90 was

431
00:25:41.080 --> 00:25:43.280
about 50%. But I think that

432
00:25:44.160 --> 00:25:46.720
was really mainly due to the theranostic.

433
00:25:47.820 --> 00:25:51.320
And frankly, we have to do this very gingerly

434
00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:54.900
because the checkpoint inhibitors do have some side effects here.

435
00:25:54.920 --> 00:25:56.480
But the reason I like

436
00:25:57.380 --> 00:26:01.200
combining this with some sort of an immunological component is that we really

437
00:26:01.300 --> 00:26:04.480
have to get every last clone if we're going to have cures.

438
00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:09.220
And a couple of years back, we developed

439
00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:13.300
a reporter, actually a PSMA reporter gene that we knocked into

440
00:26:13.360 --> 00:26:17.270
CAR T cells, and we could actually follow the CAR T cells around,

441
00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:18.880
and this mouse has leukemia,

442
00:26:19.920 --> 00:26:23.760
and you could see how after a couple of weeks, those CAR T

443
00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:26.080
cells, they do not let go of the tumor.

444
00:26:26.150 --> 00:26:28.640
So when you really see that, it really made an impression on me.

445
00:26:29.680 --> 00:26:30.620
And you can also see

446
00:26:31.620 --> 00:26:34.650
axillary lymph nodes in the animal. So we want to get every clone.

447
00:26:34.840 --> 00:26:37.280
I think we need immunology to do that.

448
00:26:38.360 --> 00:26:42.220
Also, we're seeing more high throughput experimentation being applied to

449
00:26:42.260 --> 00:26:45.900
radiopharmaceuticals and developing new PET agents using

450
00:26:45.980 --> 00:26:48.140
spheroids and organoids instead of animals.

451
00:26:48.180 --> 00:26:51.940
These are more NIH-compatible things to work with

452
00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:53.400
nowadays.

453
00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:55.320
We're also

454
00:26:56.160 --> 00:26:59.940
seeing new affinity agents. There are VHHs, peptides,

455
00:27:00.040 --> 00:27:02.480
macrocyclic peptides, small molecules.

456
00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:04.800
Antibodies are still out there in play.

457
00:27:05.520 --> 00:27:08.500
Mostly small molecules. I tend to prefer those myself.

458
00:27:08.560 --> 00:27:12.190
They tend to have better tumor penetration if you want to start going for

459
00:27:12.940 --> 00:27:16.640
other than liquid tumors. So the small molecules are

460
00:27:16.680 --> 00:27:20.400
helpful. A lot of organic chemists are now getting into the

461
00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:21.800
business where they're

462
00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:26.000
starting to apply late-stage introduction of

463
00:27:26.020 --> 00:27:27.220
fluorine-19,

464
00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:32.020
cold fluorine. They're trying to adapt that to fluorine-18

465
00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:36.120
syntheses. Fluorine-18 has a two-hour physical half-life, so you've got to be

466
00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:40.020
very quick with your syntheses. But lots of new applications

467
00:27:40.100 --> 00:27:40.380
there.

468
00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:44.880
I just saw this paper yesterday, and I thought I would mention it.

469
00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:46.940
Laura Wood's group at Johns Hopkins

470
00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:51.700
is doing-- They have a 3D

471
00:27:51.840 --> 00:27:55.160
multi-omic approach to find

472
00:27:55.540 --> 00:27:58.120
new mechanisms of tumor resistance.

473
00:27:58.980 --> 00:28:02.360
So the more biology, and that's why I see a lot of my friends here from the

474
00:28:02.400 --> 00:28:05.810
radiology chemistry world, they want to learn about biology

475
00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:09.400
so that they could leverage some of these new

476
00:28:09.460 --> 00:28:13.040
pathways so that they can be able to design ways

477
00:28:13.600 --> 00:28:15.700
of managing patients with cancer.

478
00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:20.340
So I'll end by saying that I think that the field of theranostics right

479
00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:20.760
now,

480
00:28:21.580 --> 00:28:25.540
it sort of follows Amara's law. So

481
00:28:25.580 --> 00:28:28.700
what this law says is that the shape of things to

482
00:28:28.780 --> 00:28:32.770
come is really in an S. So as we saw with

483
00:28:32.780 --> 00:28:36.530
personal computers, with cell phones, in the early

484
00:28:36.640 --> 00:28:39.720
days, we might have thought that this was hype, where we were

485
00:28:39.820 --> 00:28:43.020
overestimating, our expectations were too high.

486
00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:47.080
Eventually, our expectations were met, and

487
00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:49.720
our expectations have been exceeded.

488
00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:52.120
Think about cell phones and communications.

489
00:28:52.700 --> 00:28:56.100
I'm hoping that that's where we are now with theranostics.

490
00:28:56.160 --> 00:29:00.100
We're somewhere around here, and that we will also exceed expectations so

491
00:29:00.140 --> 00:29:04.100
that we could manage patients with cancer with this new therapy, and it'll

492
00:29:04.220 --> 00:29:07.860
come in alongside surgery, radiation, chemotherapy, and

493
00:29:07.900 --> 00:29:11.720
immunotherapy, and you'll give it consideration for your patients

